This holds for any [TopologicalSemiring](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Topology/Algebra/Ring/Basic.html#TopologicalSemiring) in place of ℝ using [MvPolynomial.induction_on](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/MvPolynomial/Basic.html#MvPolynomial.induction_on)

Also, there's already a σ around, so I think you don't need to add ι to the `variable`.
Can you add `Module.Finite R (restrictDegree σ R N)` too? It's the same proof but without the `have : Finite {s : σ →₀ ℕ | s.sum (fun _ e ↦ e) ≤ N}` part.
#find_home suggests [Mathlib.Topology.Algebra.Module.Determinant] and I'm not sure whether there's better place ...
Yeah, I'm not sure that's better.
A better home would be a new file `Topology/Algebra/MvPolynomial` with lemmas about `eval`, `eval₂` etc, see `Topology/Algebra/Polynomial`.

(untested) I think it's good to keep R and σ explicit in case you need to manually do `haveI`.
```suggestion
instance [Finite σ] (N : ℕ) : Module.Finite R (restrictDegree σ R N) :=
  have := Finsupp.finite_setOf_bounded σ N
  Module.Finite.of_basis (basisRestrictSupport R _)

instance [Finite σ] (N : ℕ) : Module.Finite R (restrictTotalDegree σ R N) :=
```

This is true for any upper bound `g : α → ℕ`, not necessary a constant. BTW, do we have a similar lemma about functions (or a generic `Set.pi univ` combinator)? If yes, then we can use `Set.Finite.preimage`.

This is basically `Set.Finite.pi` combined with finiteness of intervals. I don't think we should even have it as a lemma. It can be inlined as `(Set.Finite.pi fun _ ↦ .finite_le_nat).preimage $ Funlike.coe_injective.injOn _` (untested)

[Set.Finite.pi](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Set/Finite.html#Set.Finite.pi) produces an extra `univ` as in `∀ i ∈ univ, n i ≤ N`, which can't be easily inlined as far as I know. Moreover this lemma is used to prove that `{s : σ →₀ ℕ | s.sum (fun _ e ↦ e) ≤ N}` is also finite, by virtue of being a subset.
This is all handled by the `preimage` step. This is where you get flexibility.

> This is basically `Set.Finite.pi` combined with finiteness of intervals. I don't think we should even have it as a lemma. It can be inlined as `(Set.Finite.pi fun _ ↦ .finite_le_nat).preimage $ Funlike.coe_injective.injOn _` (untested)

I've tried to make your suggestion work, but by the time it compiled, it ended up worse than what I had in the first place. Feel free to push a better proof if you have one.

Thanks for the golf! But I don't see the point of making it private and moving it.

Well
* This lemma should not be made public, since it is a structural combination of existing lemmas
* I could inline it, but it would result in more lines

Conclusion: I should make it a private lemma where it is used so that I don't duplicate code and so that people don't find it when searching.
